explanation.p:
To verify that -\cos(x^2+1)+C is indeed the antiderivative of 
                      2x\sin(x^2+1), we need to check that \dfrac{d}{dx}
                      \left(-\cos(x^2+1)+C \right) = 2x \sin(x^2+1). To do this, we use the
                      chain rule with outside function f(x) = -\cos(x) + C and inside
                      function x^2+1: 
                        \begin{align*}
                        f(x) &= -\cos(x) + C\\
                        f'(x) &= \sin(x) && \text{Sum \& constant rule}\\
                        g(x) &= x^2+1 \\
                        g'(x) &= 2x \\
                        \dfrac{d}{dx}\left(-\cos(x^2+1) + C\right) &=
                      f'(\underbrace{x^2+1}_{g(x)}) \cdot g'(x) && \text{Chain rule}\\
                        &= \underbrace{\sin(x^2+1)}_{f'(g(x)}\cdot g'(x) \\
                        &= \sin(x^2+1) \cdot \underbrace{2x}_{g'(x)} \\
                        &= 2x \sin(x^2 + 1) && \text{Rewrite}
                        \end{align*}

