ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
We use the follwoign substitutions: 
                  \begin{align*}
                  \int x^2 e^{x^3} \, dx &= \int \overbrace{e^{x^3}}^{e^u} \cdot \overbrace{x^2
                \, dx}^{\frac{1}{3} du} \\
                  &= \int e^u \cdot \dfrac{1}{3}\, du && \text{Substitute}\\
                  &= \dfrac{1}{3} \int e^u \, du && \text{Constant multiple rule}\\
                  \\ \hline \\
                  &= \dfrac{1}{3} e^u + C && \text{Integrate}\\
                  &= \dfrac{1}{3} e^{x^3} + C && \text{Substitute back}
                  \end{align*}

question.p:
To substitute du = 3x^2 \, dx into \displaystyle \int x^2 \sqrt{x^3+1}
                 \, dx, it is helpful to rewrite du = 3x^2 \, dx as 
                 \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}}.

choice.explanation:
The integral contains x^2 \, dx. So, we solve for this
                    expression: 
                      \begin{align*}
                      du &= 3x^2 \, dx \\
                      \dfrac{1}{3} \, du &= x^2 \, dx && \text{Divide by }3 \\
                    \end{align*}

This is not equivalent to the equation du = 3x^2 \,dx.
                    Instead, dividing by 3 on both sides will leave a \dfrac{1}{3}
                    multiplying the du.

While this option does correctly substitution \sqrt{x^3 + 1}
                    as u^{1/2}, the remaining x^2 \, dx is not simply replaced by 
                    du.

Integrating, we get: 
                      \begin{align*}
                      \dfrac{1}{3}\int u^{1/2} \, du &= \dfrac{1}{3} \cdot \dfrac{1}{3/2}
                    u^{3/2} + C && \text{Power rule for antiderivatives}\\
                      &= \dfrac{1}{3}\cdot \dfrac{2}{3} u^{3/2}+C && \text{Rewrite
                    fraction}\\
                      &= \dfrac{2}{9}u^{3/2} + C&& \text{Simplify}\\
                      \end{align*}

