When x=2, we have u = 2(2)^3 + 1 = 17
Using this, we can substitute to find our definite integral written in terms of u: \begin{align*} \int_1^2 \dfrac{x^2}{2x^3+1} \, dx &= \int_1^2 \dfrac{1}{\underbrace{2x^3+1}_{u}} \cdot \underbrace{x^2\, dx}_{\frac{1}{6}du}\\ &= \int_3^{17} \frac{1}{u} \cdot \dfrac{1}{6}\, du\\ &= \frac{1}{6} \int_3^{17} \frac{1}{u} \, du\\ \end{align*}

CorrectExplanation.me:
\begin{align*} \int_1^2 \dfrac{x^2}{2x^3+1} \, dx &= \int_1^2 \dfrac{1}{\underbrace{2x^3+1}_{u}} \cdot \underbrace{x^2\, dx}_{\frac{1}{6}du}\\ &= \int_3^{17} \frac{1}{u} \cdot \dfrac{1}{6}\, du\\ &= \frac{1}{6} \int_3^{17} \frac{1}{u} \, du\\ \\ \hline \\
